Method Overloading:

- feature that allows a class to have multiple methods with the same name
  but different parameters , can overload a method as may times as you want
  (can have as many methods with the same name in a class)
   But make sure that:
   - different data types
   - different numbers of parameters
   - different order of parameters
   Advantages:
   - easier to remember one name than multiple when they have the same usability
   - code reusability
   - easier to maintain (can just go to methods body and make changes there)
   => Arguments you pass determine which one gets to execute first

   Examples:
   different number of parameters
   public static void displayValues(int a){...}
   public static void displayValues(double a){...}
   public static void displayValues(int a, int b){...}

   different order of parameters
   public static void displayValues(int a, double b){...}
   public static void displayValues(double a, int b){...}

   Ambiguous Method Call:
   - public static void calculateValues(int num1, double num2){...}
        sout(...);
   - public static void calculateValues(double num1, int num2){...}
        sout(...);

   ==>> if I call in my main method calculateValues(10, 10)
   ==>> I will get an error since 10, 10 could be int num1 and double num1 as well as
        int num2 and double num2 in either method

